  truce is dual-licensed under either of:

    * Apache License, Version 2.0 (full text in LICENSE-APACHE, also at
      <https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0>)

    * MIT License (full text in LICENSE-MIT, also at
      <https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT>)

  at your option, EXCEPT as narrowed by the Truce Framework Rider in
  Section 2. For every use other than the one described in Section 2,
  the Apache-2.0 / MIT grant applies with no further conditions, fee,
  splash screen, or revenue cap. This expressly includes building,
  shipping, and selling audio plug-ins, plug-in suites, and internal
  SDKs.


2.  THE TRUCE FRAMEWORK RIDER

2.1  Scope - Covered Framework Offerings

  For the purposes of this Section, a product or service is a
  "Covered Framework Offering" if it is a Commercial Offering (Section
  2.4) and it is either a Framework Product or a Framework Service.

  A "Framework Product" is a product where both:

    (i)  it is offered, distributed, sublicensed, or otherwise provided
         to third-party developers as a means of building audio plug-ins
         (CLAP, VST3, VST2, LV2, AU v2, AU v3, AAX, or successor
         specifications) or DAW host integrations; and

    (ii) the third-party developer's use of the product results in
         audio software that the third-party developer distributes to
         end users or to further developers.

  A "Framework Service" is a service that exposes, hosts, compiles, or
  operates truce's plug-in-building or audio-processing capabilities,
  over a network or as a hosted offering, and makes those truce-derived
  capabilities available to third-party developers as a means of
  building, packaging, running, or delivering their own audio plug-ins
  or host integrations. A service is a Framework Service whether the
  third-party developer interacts with truce directly or only through
  an interface the service places in front of it.

2.2  What is not covered

  The following are NOT Covered Framework Offerings, and their
  distribution and operation are fully covered by the permissive grant
  in Section 1:

    - any audio plug-in, plug-in suite, analyzer, or validator;

    - any hardware-vendor SDK or runtime that includes truce as an
      internal implementation detail and does not expose truce as part
      of its public developer interface;

    - any personal-use scripting layer, prototyping kit, or research
      library;

    - any wrapper or helper library targeting a specific DSP technique,
      GUI backend, or external dependency, even if useful to other
      plug-in authors as a transitive dependency;

    - any service whose users are end users of audio software rather
      than developers building their own audio plug-ins or host
      integrations, even where truce performs audio processing inside
      that service.

  A Framework License (Section 2.5), granted only by written permission
  from the Licensor, is required to operate or distribute a Covered
  Framework Offering. Free, OSI-licensed, non-commercial framework
  products and services are exempt - see Section 2.3.

2.3  Exemption - free, open-source frameworks

  The permission requirement in Section 2.1 does NOT apply to a
  Framework Product or Framework Service that simultaneously satisfies
  all of the following for the entire period of its distribution or
  operation:

    (a) Its complete source code is published and made freely
        accessible under an OSI-approved open-source license.
        "OSI-approved" means a license appearing on the Open Source
        Initiative's approved-licenses list at
        <https://opensource.org/licenses> at the time of distribution.

    (b) It is offered to its third-party developer users free of
        charge. Receiving voluntary donations, patronage (e.g. GitHub
        Sponsors, Open Collective, Patreon), or research / hobbyist
        grants is permitted under this exemption provided no
        contributor receives those funds as consideration for use of
        the framework.

    (c) It is not a Commercial Offering.

  Frameworks meeting (a)-(c) are covered by the permissive grant in
  Section 1 - no separate permission required. Authors of such
  frameworks are encouraged (but not required) to notify the Licensor
  and may be listed in the project's ecosystem documentation.

  If a framework subsequently becomes a Commercial Offering, the
  exemption ceases to apply from the date the Commercial Offering
  begins; continued distribution or operation from that date requires a
  written Framework License under Section 2.5. Audio software already
  built under the prior exemption is unaffected.

2.4  Commercial Offering

  A "Commercial Offering" means any product, service, or arrangement
  that:

    (i)   requires payment, subscription, license fee, royalty, or
          other monetary consideration for access to, use of,
          modification of, or distribution of the framework or its
          functionality;

    (ii)  is dual-licensed by its publisher under commercial terms in
          parallel with the open-source license referenced in Section
          2.3(a);

    (iii) is bundled with, or used to gate access to, a paid product,
          paid support contract, paid hosting service, paid training,
          paid certification, or paid consulting offering where the
          framework itself (rather than the paying customer's own audio
          software produced with the framework) is the primary value
          being sold; or

    (iv)  is offered to the public under any other arrangement whose
          principal purpose is commercial advantage or monetary
          compensation to the framework's publisher or operator.

2.5  Framework License grants

  The Licensor is under no obligation to grant a Framework License.
  When granted, the Licensor may impose any terms (including but not
  limited to attribution, contribution-back, scope limits, financial
  terms, revocation conditions, and time limits) as a condition of the
  grant. Past grants do not bind future decisions.

  Requests should be sent to `framework-licensing@truce.audio` (or
  initiated as a private discussion on the truce-audio GitHub
  organization, with the maintainers tagged). A well-formed request
  describes:

    (a) the product or service being built, its developer audience, and
        what that audience receives from it;

    (b) the role truce plays inside it - core, one backend among
        several, internal implementation detail, or otherwise;

    (c) the distribution or commercialization model under which it
        reaches its third-party developers; and

    (d) the proposed terms of the requested Framework License,
        including any attribution, time, scope, or financial terms the
        requester is willing to accept.

  The Licensor will acknowledge any well-formed request within two to
  four weeks of receipt. Acknowledgement is not a grant. The Licensor
  reserves the right to deny a request without detailed reasoning.

  If you are unsure whether your product or service is a Covered
  Framework Offering, or whether the Section 2.3 exemption applies,
  contact the Licensor before shipping. Ambiguities in the boundary
  between the permissive grant and this Rider are to be resolved in
  favor of the permissive grant unless the use is plainly a Covered
  Framework Offering without satisfying the Section 2.3 exemption.


